<div id="content" lang="en" dir="ltr">
Macros and other useful stuff useful to all sorcerers. <p>
Hopefully this will be the basis of a 'sorcerer starting kit' that could almost ship with the game directly. 
</p>
<h3 id="head-32536ab125e45499a3ea859bb434c59a5058e2f4">The macro file itself (spells are alphabetical)</h3>

<pre># Macros
A:f*.
P:\[alt-F]

A:m@Cast\sa\sspell\n
C:0:\r

A:m@Cast\sa\sspell\n@Dig\n
P:\[alt-A]

A:m@Cast\sa\sspell\n@Disarm\n
P:\[alt-T]

A:m@Cast\sa\sspell\n@Ent's\sPotion\n
P:\[alt-R]

A:m@Cast\sa\sspell\n@Essence\sof\sSpeed\n
P:\[alt-S]

A:m@Cast\sa\sspell\n@Fireflash\n*.
P:\[alt-J]

A:m@Cast\sa\sspell\n@Geyser\n*.
C:0:^J

A:m@Cast\sa\sspell\n@Globe of Light\n
C:0:^L

A:m@Cast\sa\sspell\n@Identify\n
P:\[alt-I]

A:m@Cast\sa\sspell\n@Manathrust\n*.
C:0:J

A:m@Cast\sa\sspell\n@Sense\sHidden\nm@Cast\sa\sspell\n@Sense\sMonsters\n
P:\[alt-E]

A:m@Cast\sa\sspell\n@Vision\n
P:\[alt-D]

A:m@Cast\sa\sspell\n@Healing\n
P:\[alt-H]

</pre><h3 id="head-9bd7ddeff82491ca2da94d37a54f48c8da1c40ad">Macro comments</h3>
<p>
The use of @ when making a macro makes sure you don't have to bother with which book or worn item the spell is in. 
</p>
<p>
Since sorcerers can cast nearly all spells, other spellcasters can use this macro file as is, simply ignoring spells they can't cast or deleting the relevant macros from their files. 
</p>
<p>
This list could use some necromancy additions (necromancy, regeneration, etc) and eventually every useful spell (on the other hand, it will indirectly provide a list of which spells are almost never used). 
</p>
<p>
By the way what does the first macro do? 
</p>
<h3 id="head-3e69f54ebf0cc11bd7468a6bd765ef3e59ac4931">Inscriptions</h3>
<p>
Put !k!s!d!v on spellbook you want to keep. This will allow the automatizer to get rid of noninscribed duplicates safely. 
</p>
<p>
Also inscribe your spell-inscribable wearable items as !k!s!d!v too just in case. 
</p>
<h3 id="head-9033b5faf34c3f8368fbce03c3f47fbf09725107">Automatizer</h3>
<p>
It's mostly about destroying all bad/average weapons, and good weapons a bit later. 
</p>
<p>
An automatizer tweak should be provided for people who have the drain spell( they can make good use of boring wands ). 
</p>
<p>
<strong><a href="./NeilStevens">NeilStevens</a></strong>: <a href=".www.hakubi.us/tome/automat.atm">http://www.hakubi.us/tome/automat.atm</a> has several rules useful for sorcerors.  It automatically picks up and inscribes books. 
</p>
<h3 id="head-ff11f0da0a4cd245270f188d8a7299b4084d0328">Chatter</h3>
<p>
<a href="./SimonSorc">SimonSorc</a>: The macros' chosen keys could be better... 
</p>
<p>
<strong><a href="./NeilStevens">NeilStevens</a></strong>: They keys I use have grown organically as I've added more spells to the list.  Few rules govern them.  I do like having attacks on the home row of my right hand, though.  Utility spells then by default go on the left.  Frequently-cast spells on the index finger seems to be a pattern, too. 
</p>
<p>
<strong><a href="./MayLith">MayLith</a></strong>: I'm going to be bringing over the in-game Macro FAQ soon. We can break it down/rebuild it (a la the 6 million dollar man) as needed... but I suggest one little bitty idea: If actual keys are referenced (rather than patterns like 'right hand' which is great) then be sure to mention whether the QWERTY or DVORAK keyboard is being used. 
</p>
<p>
<strong><a href="./ReenenLaurie">ReenenLaurie</a></strong>: A dvorak keyboard?  Wow, never heard of it.  Can you type out a map for me (just out of curiosity).   
</p>
<p>
Like  
</p>

<pre>QWERTYUIOP
ASDFGHJKL
ZXCVBNM
</pre><p>
And where does one use a keyboard like that? 
</p>
<p>
<strong><a href="./MayLith">MayLith</a></strong>: You can use it anywhere if you have control over the keymap. 
</p>
<p>
Example link: <a class="external" href=".www.mwbrooks.com/dvorak/"><img src="./wiki/rightsidebar/img/moin-www.png" alt="[WWW]" height="11" width="11">Introducing the Dvorak keyboard</a> 
</p>
<p>
DVORAK is supposed to be <em>far</em> better in terms of efficiency in typing (at least in the English language) than the QWERTY one. I'm a very fast QWERTY touch-typer as it is -- I average 90-120 wpm if I'm not distracted. I have an interest in converting over to DVORAK, but the big prob is that at work, it'll always be QWERTY, and I'd probably get way too confused (given my dyslexia) trying to go back and forth between them. I still might try one of these days though... 
</p>
<p>
The QWERTY or DVORAK keyboard really doesn't matter in terms of macros, except in which key combos might be most convenient/pain-free, which is why I brought it up. 
</p>
<p>
<strong><a href="./ReenenLaurie">ReenenLaurie</a></strong>: Wow... 90-120... I can do about 40, and I'm fine with that. 
</p>
<p>
I looked at the layout... and EEEEK... Vowels and stuff on the left...  But it would be an interesting read to know why the qwerty was the standard.  1800's you say? 
</p>
<p>
I can't see people changing to this... Ever.  Though I've been wrong before. 
</p>

    <ul>

 <a href="./MassimilianoMarangio">MassimilianoMarangio</a>: Here is the Wikipedia article with some historical notes about the <a class="interwiki" title="WikiPedia" href=".www.wikipedia.com/wiki/Qwerty"><img src="./wiki/rightsidebar/img/moin-inter.png" alt="[WikiPedia]" height="16" width="16">Qwerty</a> layout. 
    </ul>


<p>
For those interested (I dunno what happened to ~): 
<pre>  PYFGCRL
AOEUIDHTNS
 QJKXBMWVZ
</pre>
</p>
<p>
But I think more important than the letters is the rest of the apostrophe's etc. that moved.  (And that'd be too hard to show here, follow the link). 
</p>
<p>
(But we're WAYYYYY of topic here) 
</p>
<p>
<strong><a href="./MayLith">MayLith</a></strong>: I didn't write the website I referenced. However, from here and there in my long years of geekdom, I've heard occasionally of folks who <em><strong>swear</strong></em> by DVORAK, which is why I brought it up.  
</p>
<p>
Actually, I wonder as a thought-problem whether it might have made regular typewriters work better; I learned typing on a manual typewriter and when I got going fast the little lever-things would always get caught on each other.... Sort of akin to the famous/infamous type-ahead buffer issue with the old macs, IBM 286, 386, 486's etc. 
</p>
<p>
<strong><a href="./PaulMoore">PaulMoore</a></strong>: I understand the P:\[alt-F] stuff, I assume this means that the key is Alt-F. But what is C:0:\r (used in a couple of places)? 
</p>

    <ul>

 <strong><a href="./ZizzoTheInfinite">ZizzoTheInfinite</a></strong>: The <tt>C:</tt> line defines a keymap instead of a macro.  Of course, I'm not entirely clear about the difference between the two, so this may not be of much help... <img src="./wiki/rightsidebar/img/redface.png" alt=":o" height="15" width="15">  In particular, the <tt>0</tt> means that this keymap is only available in non-roguelike mode; a <tt>1</tt> would define a roguelike-mode keymap, and higher numbers would correspond to other keymap modes, if we had any... <p>
 <strong><a href="./NeilStevens">NeilStevens</a></strong>: I don't remember why those ended up different. 
</p>
<p>
 <strong><a href="./PaulMoore">PaulMoore</a></strong>: So 'J' maps to manathrust, and the return key to "cast a spell"? Neat - it never occurred to me that "normal" keys could be mapped like that. 
</p>
</ul>

